    en: "NY law prohibits employers from asking job applicants and current employees about their pay history. The ban is in NY Labor Law section 194-a, which took effect statewide in January 2020. The law applies to all NY employers regardless of size. Employers cannot rely on past salary in setting an offer; they cannot retaliate against an applicant for refusing to share salary history; and they cannot ask former employers for salary information about the applicant. The applicant can voluntarily share past pay if they choose, but cannot be required to. NY's separate pay-transparency law (Labor Law 194-b) requires employers with 4 or more employees to post the salary range for any NY-connected job posting."
